    <fileheader>
        <author> Jon S. Berndt</author>
        <filecreationdate> 2000-06-20 </filecreationdate>
        <version> S&amp;C 4th Ed. case study aircraft </version>
        <description>
            The data for this aircraft model has been taken from the F-16 model described
            in the book by Stevens and Lewis, "Aircraft Control and Simulation, 2nd. Ed."

            The F-16 model is a high-fidelity, full-envelope, nonlinear, six-degree-of-freedom
            aircraft simulation model. The aerodynamic model is a function of angle-of-attack,
            sideslip angle, and elevator, aileron, and rudder deflections. The aerodynamic data
            is valid for angles-of-attack from -10 to 45 degrees, and for sideslip angles from
            -30 to 30 degrees. A detailed development of the aerodynamic model can be found
            in the NASA technical report by Nguyen, Ogburn, Gilbert, et. al., "Simulator Study
            of Stall/Post-Stall Characteristics of a Fighter Airplane With Relaxed Longitudinal
            Static Stability," NASA TP-1538, December 1979.
        </description>
        <reference refID="None" author="Richard Murray" title="http://www.cds.caltech.edu/~murray/projects/afosr95-vehicles/models/f16/" date="n/a"/>
    </fileheader>

